      "id":"money/2013/oct/17/invesco-perpetual-small-investors-woodford-departing",
      "sectionId":"money",
      "sectionName":"Money",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-17T12:03:42Z",
      "webTitle":"Perpetual motion leaves Invesco investors looking for next big thing",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/money/2013/oct/17/invesco-perpetual-small-investors-woodford-departing",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/money/2013/oct/17/invesco-perpetual-small-investors-woodford-departing",
      "fields":{
        "newspaperPageNumber":"3",
        "trailText":"<p>What should an army of small investors do now that Invesco fund manager Neil Woodford is departing? We quiz the experts</p>",
        "headline":"Perpetual motion leaves Invesco investors looking for next big thing",
        "body":"<p>Neil Woodford is that rare beast in the City jungle: an investor who has consistently overperformed over the long term. This week he stunned financial advisers and his devoted army of small investors when he revealed he will quit <a href=\"http://www.invescoperpetual.co.uk/portal/site/ip/home/\" title=\"Invesco Perpetual website\">Invesco Perpetual</a>, where he looks after an astonishing £33bn of their money.</p><p>Woodford joined Invesco Perpetual 25 years ago, and investors who put their cash into his funds early on have made huge returns. Someone investing £1,000 in October 1990 in Invesco Perpetual High Income would have seen it grow to £23,265 by the end of September 2013, compared to £9,714 if they had left the money tracking the FTSE All-Share index.</p><p>But much of Woodford's success has occurred over the past 15 years, in part because he refused to be drawn into the internet stock bubble of 1999-2000, and because he bought tobacco companies at a time when most other investors thought they were doomed.</p><p>Woodford has skilfully satisified both growth investors looking for a fund as a nest egg for the future, and the income-hungry investor fed up with 2% returns on cash Isas, who has enjoyed dividends worth 3%-4% a year plus capital growth.</p><figure data-media-id='gu-image-420252885'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Money/Pix/pictures/2013/10/17/1382011260637/Invesco-returns-graph-001.jpg' alt='Invesco returns graph' width='460' height='274' class='gu-image'/><figcaption>Graphic: Hargreaves Lansdown</figcaption></figure><p>Brian Dennehy of advisers Dennehy Weller says: \"Woodford's success over the past 15 years has to a large extent been based on one huge bet – one we have called the biggest and longest bet in fund management history: a consistently large overweight in defensives, and in particular utilities, tobacco, and pharmaceuticals. Would any other manager have had the foresight to begin this strategy, and the fortitude to continue with it over such a prolonged period? I don't think so.\"</p><p>But the size of the Woodford funds has become a worry for some advisers, who fear that giant ones can do little more than replicate the FTSE index. Around £500m has come out of the Woodford funds over the past year, Dennehy says. \"This suggests that some time ago the retail funds market became saturated with the Woodford funds. The risk for Invesco Perpetual now is that a significant leak could turn into a flood.\"</p><p>Others point out that aura around Woodford has blinded some advisers to the other income funds that have matched or beaten his performance in recent years. Gary Potter, who spends his time analysing investment managers for his Navigator fund-of-funds business, says: \"We have not owned any Woodford funds for a number of years. Yes, he is a tremendous fund manager with a tremendous track  record, and he's the best of anyone who has managed a large amount of assets and still been able to outperform.</p><p>\"But however good a ship's captain is, the bigger the boat you put him in charge of, the harder it is to navigate. Clive Beagles at JO UK Hambro Equity Income has outperformed Woodford over the past five years, making a 128% gain for investors compared to 71% in the Invesco Perpetual funds.\"</p><p>Over the next few months, small investors will be assailed by fund management groups wanting to attract them away from Invesco Perpetual. Guardian Money asked advisers what they are recommending to clients.</p><h2><strong>Which funds are affected?</strong></h2><p>A wide variety of funds that invest in UK shares for an income, mostly under the Invesco Perpetual name, but also some under the St James Place name. Many savers will be invested in Woodford funds through their pension schemes, with Prudential, Standard Life, Aviva and Legal &amp; General all offering his income funds under their investment ranges.</p><p>Woodford directly manages Invesco Perpetual High Income (with £14bn under management); Invesco Perpetual Income (£10.5bn); Invesco Perpetual UK Equity Pension (£500m); and the Edinburgh Investment Trust (£1.3bn). He also manages the equity components of Invesco Perpetual Monthly Income Plus (£3.8bn) and Invesco Perpetual Distribution (£2.6bn).</p><h2><strong>Where is he going?</strong></h2><p>Woodford leaves Invesco Perpetual in April 2014, and in a statement said he would be opening his own investment management company.</p><p>\"My decision to leave is a personal one based on my views about where I see long-term opportunities in the fund management industry. My intention is to establish a new fund management business serving institutional and retail clients as soon as possible after 29 April 2014.\" He says he won't make any other announcements about the new business until after he has left.</p><h2><strong>Why is he going?</strong></h2><p>The unconfirmed speculation is that Woodford will be happier running smaller funds again, where, according to Alan Miller of SCM Private (and better known as one of the key figures behind New Star Asset Management), he will be able to buy his favourite small companies. \"Whatever his stake or incentive was in Invesco, he will almost certainly be much better off holding the majority of 'Woodford asset management',\" Miller adds.</p><h2><strong>Should investors stick with Invesco?</strong></h2><p>Mark Barnett, who has been at Invesco for 17 years, will take over the management of Woodford's funds. Barnett has actually beaten Woodford's performance since he took over management of the Invesco Perpetual UK Strategic Income fund, says Adrian Lowcock of Hargreaves Lansdown, returning 49.9% since January 2006 compared to Woodford's return of 35.3%. But Barnett's fund is substantially smaller at £285m, compared to the billions run by Woodford, and he has invested less in healthcare and has a larger exposure to financials. At Bestinvest, Jason Hollands says: \"[Barnett] has a lot of similar shareholdings to Woodford and is a safe pair of hands.\"</p><p>But others wonder how Barnett will progress post-Woodford. \"His top 10 holdings do appear to reflect 'the hand of Woodford'. What happens without that guiding hand? It is a huge unknown for investors,\" Dennehy says.</p><h2><strong>What are the alternatives?</strong></h2><p>There are plenty. The two giant equity income funds Potter rates are <a href=\"http://www.trustnet.com/Factsheets/Factsheet.aspx?fundCode=8AI&amp;univ=U\" title=\"Artemis fund\">Artemis Income</a>, managed by Adrian Frost, and Beagles' <a href=\"http://www.trustnet.com/Factsheets/Factsheet.aspx?fundCode=JOF98&amp;univ=U\" title=\"JO Hambro fund\">JO Hambro fund</a>. But with the Artemis fund nearly £6bn in size, and the JO Hambro fund more than £2bn, they may both arguably suffer the same size problems as Woodford.</p><p>Smaller funds that have enjoyed strong performance and are tipped by Potter include <a href=\"http://www.chelvertonam.com/home/chelverton-uk-equity-income-fund-oeic.php\" title=\"Chelverton UK Equity Income fund\">Chelverton UK Equity Income</a>, which he says \"has been the absolutely number one performer this year, yet it still only has £140m under management.\" He also likes <a href=\"http://www.trustnet.com/Factsheets/Factsheet.aspx?fundCode=K4F41&amp;univ=U\" title=\"Standard Life UK Equity Income fund\">Standard Life UK Equity Income Unconstrained</a>, <a href=\"http://www.riverandmercantile.com/investment_divisions/uk_equity_division/r_m_uk_income_fund\" title=\"River  Mercantile UK Equity Income fund\">River &amp; Mercantile UK Equity Income</a>, <a href=\"http://www.ardevora.com/index.php/ardevora/products\" title=\"Ardevora UK Income fund\">Ardevora UK Income</a> and <a href=\"http://www.trustnet.com/Factsheets/Factsheet.aspx?fundCode=KRF58&amp;univ=U\" title=\"Cazenove UK Equity Income fund\">Cazenove UK Equity Income</a>.</p><p>Lowcock also tips Artemis Income, as well as <a href=\"http://www.trustnet.com/Factsheets/Factsheet.aspx?fundCode=BEINC&amp;univ=U\" title=\"Rathbone Income fund\">Rathbone Income</a>, while at Bestinvest Hollands also likes Artemis Income, as well as <a href=\"http://www.trustnet.com/Factsheets/Factsheet.aspx?fundCode=ESHII&amp;univ=U\" title=\"Threadneedle UK Equity Income fund\">Threadneedle UK Equity Income</a>, <a href=\"http://www.trustnet.com/Factsheets/Factsheet.aspx?fundCode=FIMXIE&amp;univ=U\" title=\"Fidelity Moneybuilder Dividend fund\">Fidelity Moneybuilder Dividend</a> and <a href=\"http://www.trustnet.com/Factsheets/Factsheet.aspx?fundCode=UFF54&amp;univ=U\" title=\"Unicorn UK Income fund\">Unicorn UK Income</a>.</p><p>Investors more keen on growth rather than income should consider <a href=\"http://www.mandg.co.uk/investor/funds/recovery-fund/gb0031289100/overview.aspx\" title=\"MG Recovery fund\">M&amp;G Recovery</a> or <a href=\"http://www.trustnet.com/Factsheets/Factsheet.aspx?fundCode=SZUKMI&amp;univ=U\" title=\"Schroder UK Mid 250 fund\">Schroder UK Mid 250</a>, Dennehy says. \"For a fund with momentum in its favour right now, opt for <a href=\"http://www.trustnet.com/Factsheets/Factsheet.aspx?fundCode=S6F73&amp;univ=U\" title=\"Standard Life UK Opportunities fund\">Standard Life UK Opportunities</a>.\"</p><h2><strong>Should I wait and see what Woodford's new offering is?</strong></h2><p>Probably. As Lowcock says: \"We do not believe investors should rush to a decision – in our view Woodford is an exceptional manager and will continue to work hard at achieving strong performance for investors until he departs.\"</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/420248293|2013-10-17T12:53:00Z|ed5126aa85ef493087efbcc283b221fa7b460c6f -->",
