      "id":"money/2013/oct/16/banks-building-societies-slash-savings-rates",
      "sectionId":"money",
      "sectionName":"Money",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-16T16:21:11Z",
      "webTitle":"Banks and building societies slash savings rates",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/money/2013/oct/16/banks-building-societies-slash-savings-rates",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/money/2013/oct/16/banks-building-societies-slash-savings-rates",
      "fields":{
        "trailText":"But experts see some 'light at the end of the tunnel' as fixed-rate bonds show signs of rising",
        "headline":"Banks and building societies slash savings rates",
        "body":"<p>September saw the biggest cuts to savings rates in recent memory, with returns on more than 240 accounts lowered during the month, according to savings analysts.</p><p>Nationwide and Sainsbury's were among the account providers slashing rates, with some customers seeing interest cut by 1%. However, in a glimmer of hope for savers experts are also reporting the first rate increases to the fixed-rate savings bond market in many months.</p><p>Since the government introduced the <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/funding-for-lending\" title=\"\">Funding for Lending</a> programme in the summer of 2012, Britain's savers have endured a torrid time with many watching as their savings income has been halved. The latest round of cuts in September are possibly a result of the Bank of England's recent confirmation that base rates will remain at current levels for some time.</p><p>Anna Bowes, a founder of the <a href=\"https://www.savingschampion.co.uk/\" title=\"\">SavingsChampion.co.uk</a> website that tracks rates paid by banks and building societies, said: \"September was a terrible month for existing savers with 241 rate cuts across the market.</p><p>\"At the same time, though, several firms started vying to be at the top of the fixed-rate savings bonds tables. As a result, rates for those willing to tie their money up for a set period have started to look a little better. It's long overdue and good to see that there is finally some light at the end of the tunnel. British savers have endured a terrible year.\"</p><p>Last month, Bowes says, Nationwide lowered the interest rate paid on its Loyalty Saver Issue 1 by 0.5% to 2.1%; Sainsbury's halved its Cash Isa rate from 2% to 1%; while NS&amp;I Income Bonds rate dropped by 0.5% to 1.25%. The Newcastle building society cuts its Loyalty Access Isa (Issue 2) by 0.75% to 1.5%.</p><p>So far in October, Sainsbury's has cut its Easy Saver by 0.7% to 1%, while the rates paid by Derbyshire, Cheshire and Dunfermline Platinum Notice accounts have all been halved to 1.25%.</p><p></p><p>Meanwhile, over the past six weeks, fixed-rate savings products have been creeping up. Bowes says those prepared to lock away at least £1,000 for five years will now get 3.15% at the West Bromwich building society. Birmingham Midshires has the top paying one-year bond – 2% – while Close Brothers is paying 2.3% for two years on balances in excess of £10,000. Aldermore pays 2.6% to those putting at least £1,000 in its three-year bond.</p><p>Despite the rise in fixed-rate savings, those looking for instant access are still suffering low rates. SavingsChampion says the average of the easy access, best-buy accounts remains stuck around 1.5% – half the 3.2% savers were getting on average in August 2012.</p><p>A spokeswoman for Moneyfacts said rates on fixed-term deals were slowly rising again. \"As the mortgage market has seen a resurgence with the recent launch of the government's Help to Buy scheme, banks are now looking for extra funds, by increasing long-term fixed rate deals,\" she said.</p><p>\"Longer term fixed rates and Isas have seen a resurgence – these offer the highest rates in the market and therefore grab attention of savers looking to make the most of their money. Because the market is still volatile, customers would be wise to spread their savings across short-term fix and easy access, as they then have the choice of moving some of their investment quickly with market movements.\"</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/420169258|2013-10-17T12:53:00Z|c5e4cdca6c62a226b3c28368448f37aa35d392d5 -->",
