        "trailText":"'Aggressive' price drop is likely to hasten the update of superfast mobile internet access",
        "headline":"EE cuts cost of 4G access in move likely to be followed by O2 and Vodafone",
        "body":"<p>EE has cut the cost of access to its 4G network, offering handset plans from £19 a month in what one analyst calls an \"aggressive\" move that rivals are likely to follow.</p><p>Similar cuts at O2 and Vodafone are now likely, and will hasten the spread of superfast mobile internet access. This is despite the fact that their 4G networks, which <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/technology/2013/aug/28/vodafone-o2-launch-4g\" title=\"\">launched nine months after EE's</a>, are still in the early stages of rollout and remain far from nationwide.</p><p>Vodafone's entry-level offer for a 4G handset plan is £34, while O2 offers a similar deal at £32.</p><p>\"This is an aggressive move from EE that considerably widens its target market for 4G,\" said analyst Kester Mann at CCS Insight. \"The move will force Vodafone and O2 to reassess their pricing strategy.\"</p><p>EE's entry-level plan is now just £2 more than the cheapest equivalent 3G rates on its Orange and T-Mobile networks, which do not offer 4G. Previously, EE's cheapest 4G plan was £26.</p><p>The UK's largest network operator, created through the merger of Orange and T-Mobile, has been pushing its EE brand at the expense of the older names, amid speculation that they may eventually be replaced. However, the majority of its 26 million customers are still on either Orange or T-Mobile contracts, with just over 1 million signed to the EE network to date.</p><p>\"This clearly offers greater incentive for existing Orange and T-Mobile customers to upgrade to EE,\" said Mann, \"and casts further doubt on the long-term future for these brands.\"</p><p>The arrival of cheaper 4G handsets from Nokia and Samsung has enabled EE to drop its prices. Those signing up for its  £18.99 plan will get 1,000 minutes of calls a month, unlimited texts and a small 500 Megabit bundle of data. They will have to pay some money upfront for better handsets – for example £50 for the Samsung Galaxy Ace 3, £100 for the Nokia Lumia 625, and £380 for the iPhone 5C.</p><p>\"The general push of this is making 4G more accessible to the mass market through offering it on prepay and on cheaper handsets,\" said telecoms expert James Barford at Enders Analysis.</p><p>The price drop comes ahead of Three's 4G launch, expected in December. Three has said it will offer the faster internet service at no extra cost to existing customers.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/420143379|2013-10-17T12:53:00Z|aaa9d990db3df2be70160e2c74f68cf810ab6acc -->",
