        "headline":"Car insurance premiums buck the trend",
        "body":"<p>Some good news at last for consumers hit by rising prices pretty much everywhere else: car insurance premiums are apparently plummeting. The average cost of an annual comprehensive policy has fallen almost 24% – or £206 – over the last two-and-a-half years to £652, according to according a report by Confused.com, the price comparison website, and Towers Watson, a consultant.</p><p></p><p>Premiums have dropped by 3.9%, or £26, in the past three months alone, the report found, and are expected to keep falling. This is thanks partly to an <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/money/2012/dec/21/women-car-insurance-eu\" title=\"\">EC gender directive</a> that came into force in December 2012 meaning insurers are no longer able to use gender as a factor when pricing insurance.</p><p></p><p>Female motorists have traditionally enjoyed far lower premiums than their male counterparts, as men are statistically more likely to have an accident. However, the average difference between premiums for men and women now stands at just £30. The introduction of telematics, or black box technology, is also credited with driving down costs for those who can prove they are better drivers.</p><p></p><p>However, while premiums for young men have fallen substantially since gender equality was introduced, for young women they've risen substantially. The average comprehensive cover for women aged 17 to 20 rose by 9.1% in the last 12 months to an eye-watering £1,862. In comparison, the average male driver aged between 17 and 20 have seen their premiums sink by a hefty 29.2% in the last year, from £3,314 to £2,345 – or £969 less.</p><p></p><p>Have you noticed a reduction in what you pay – or have your premiums managed to buck the overall trend?</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/420149227|2013-10-17T12:53:00Z|4143309659fd4fa1109420373524738a781f54d8 -->",
