        "body":"<p>The UK's biggest star fund manager, Neil Woodford, is to quit Invesco Perpetual to open his own fund management business in April in a move that has stunned the asset management industry.</p><p>Woodford, who personally manages funds at Invesco Perpetual totalling £24.6bn and co-manages another £6.4bn, with vast stakes in Glaxo, AstraZeneca, BT and several big tobacco companies, will leave the company on 29 April after 25 years. He said the decision to move was a personal one and that he leaves on good terms.</p><p>\"I leave the company on good terms and remain fully committed to my fund management responsibilities at Invesco Perpetual until my departure. The Invesco Perpetual High Income Fund, Invesco Perpetual Income Fund and other client mandates will be transitioned into the hands of my long-standing, experienced colleagues. I wish my colleagues all the best for the future,\" said Woodford.</p><p>\"My decision to leave is a personal one based on my views about where I see long-term opportunities in the fund management industry. My intention is to establish a new fund management business serving institutional and retail clients as soon as possible after 29 April 2014. There will be no further comment at this stage. Further announcements about the new business will be made after I have left.\"</p><p>Recent performance of Woodford's flagship funds has been middling, with Income and High Income both currently ranked third quartile over one year. But over three years he remains a top quartile performer.</p><p>His departure will be a major blow for Invesco Perpetual, which is likely to see billions of pounds flow out to join Woodford when he opens his new venture. The company said his fund responsibilities would shift to Mark Barnett and the Invesco Perpetual UK equities team.</p><p>The news has rocked the investment world, in which Woodford has earned hero status. On Twitter, the editor of Citywire, Gavin Lumsden said: \"Invesco must be wetting themselves. Neil Woodford setting up a new fund manager.\"</p><p>Patrick Connolly of financial advisers Chase de Vere, said: \"This is terrible news for Invesco Perpetual and will be a cause for concern for many investors who trust their investments and pensions with Neil Woodford. It will be impossible for Invesco Perpetual to replace Woodford with somebody of similar standing because, particularly in the world of UK equity income funds, there is nobody of similar standing. However, there is no reason for investors to panic. Woodford is still running the same investment funds today as he did yesterday and this will continue until next April.\"</p><p>However, Connolly added that he felt investors should not switch automatically to Woodford's new funds, suggesting alternatives such as Artemis Income, Threadneedle UK Equity Income and Rathbone Income.</p><p>At Invesco Perpetual, Mark Armour, CEO said the company has planned for Woodford's succession \"for many years\". He said: \"Neil has served clients of Invesco Perpetual with commitment for over 25 years. It has been a privilege for us all to work alongside him, and I understand that, after 25 years, he is ready for new challenges.\"</p><p>He added:  \"We have planned for succession for many years and have built a world-class investment culture that develops and supports gifted and experienced managers.  Mark Barnett is an exceptional fund manager who has the same active, value-driven investment approach and long-term focus as Neil. A key member of the UK Equities team for 17 years, Mark has a first-quartile track record over one, three and five years.\"</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/420030786|2013-10-17T12:53:00Z|93172798619180ec810ce856ab7b38976dab590d -->",
