      "sectionId":"money",
      "sectionName":"Money",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-09-18T08:07:55Z",
      "webTitle":"Can we use the government's Help to Buy scheme if we rent out a property?",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/money/2013/sep/18/help-to-buy-rented-property",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/money/2013/sep/18/help-to-buy-rented-property",
      "fields":{
        "trailText":"We have to leave our family home and move to Leicester and are reluctant to sell the house we rent out",
        "headline":"Can we use the government's Help to Buy scheme if we rent out a property?",
        "body":"<p><strong>Q</strong> Can you get the government's Help to Buy scheme if you have a rental property already?</p><p>We have a family home in Cleethorpes and need to move to Leicester for work. Our home in Cleethorpes is valued at around £250,000 and we have around £140,000 left to pay on our repayment mortgage. My husband also has a house from before we met which is also on a repayment mortgage. This house is valued at around £200,000 and we have around £130,000 left to pay on that one. We rent this one out and we don't want to sell it.</p><p>If we sold the house in Cleethorpes, could we (with scraping together around about £50,000 in savings) pay off the mortgage on the rental house and then apply for the Help to Buy scheme to buy another house in Leicester which would be our family home. This would leave us with the rental house as our pension plan and just the one mortgage.</p><p>I would be really grateful if you could answer this question as I can't find any advice on the web about it at all. <strong>AB</strong></p><p></p><p><strong>A</strong> You'll find a lot of information about the government's current Help to Buy scheme in the <a href=\"http://www.helptobuy.org.uk/wpcontent/uploads/2013/06/Help-to-Buy-equity-loan-buyers-guide.pdf\" title=\"\">Help to Buy Buyer's Guide (pdf)</a> published on the <a href=\"http://www.helptobuy.org.uk/\" title=\"\">Help to Buy website</a>. This categorically states that \"the property purchased [using the Help to Buy scheme] must be your only residence. Help to Buy is not available to assist buy-to-let investors or those who will own any property other than their Help to Buy property after completing their purchase\". More seriously, \"applicants who make fraudulent claims for Help to Buy assistance will be liable to criminal prosecution\" so just not mentioning your rental property is not an option.</p><p>The first part of Help to Buy, which came into place in April, can only be used on new-build properties. Had you been eligible, you would have been expected to put down a cash deposit of 5% on your new home in Leicester, take out a Help to Buy mortgage of 75% with the remaining 20% of the purchase price being funded by an equity loan from government. The Help to Buy mortgage guarantee scheme which will apply to both newly built and existing homes will be available from 1 January 2014. However, the fact you plan to own more than one property means you will not qualify to use it.</p><p>Given that you can't get government help with buying your new home, and you don't want to sell the rental property, your options are limited. One option would be to keep the current mortgage on the rental property and use the £110,000 from selling your home (assuming you sell for £250,000 and pay off the outstanding mortgage of £140,000) to put towards buying your new home in Leicester. Alternatively, if you are determined to clear the mortgage on the rental property, you could use the proceeds from selling your home together with some of your £50,000 in savings to do just that.</p><p>However, that would leave you with only £30,000 of your savings to put down as a deposit on the Leicester house. Assuming you would get a mortgage of 80% of the value on your new home, this would buy you a property costing £150,000.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/417533454|2013-10-17T12:53:00Z|fbd378e79bdfe3c6b61fd6aaa9e8f093c8f9644c -->",
